    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{4}{y+3}-\frac{8y}{y^{2}-9}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{4}{y-3}, y\ne -3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{4}{y+3}-\frac{8y}{y^{2}-9}} 
      \amp = {\frac{4}{y+3}}-\frac{8 y}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{4\cdot({y-3})}{({y+3})\cdot({y-3})} -\frac{8 y}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{4\mathopen{}\left(y-3\right)-8y}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{4y-12-8y}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{-4y-12}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{-4\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = {-\frac{4}{y-3}, y\ne -3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{y+3}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>y \ne {-3}</m>.</p>
</solution>
